{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1ff0c32-93b0-4b81-aa36-31b73c57a64b","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET 11 raised the minimum x86-64 CPU baseline.** Previous .NET versions targeted the original x86-64 instruction set (SSE/SSE2 only). .NET 11 bumped this to **x86-64-v2**, which requires:\n\n- **SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2**\n- **POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B**\n\nYour 2012-era node likely has a CPU (e.g., older AMD Phenom/Opteron lacking SSSE3, or a pre-Nehalem Xeon) that's missing one or more of these. The runtime checks at startup and refuses to run.\n\n**Your other platforms are unaffected** — the ARM64 baseline for both Windows and Linux didn't change in a way that impacts SQ1 or Cortex-A72 (RPi 4).\n\n## Diagnose it\n\nOn the failing node, run:\n\n```bash\ngrep -oP 'sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\nIf any of those five are missing, that's your culprit.\n\n## Options\n\n| Option | Tradeoff |\n|---|---|\n| **Replace the hardware** | Any CPU from ~2010+ (Intel Westmere / AMD Bulldozer) meets v2 |\n| **Stay on .NET 10 LTS** for that node | .NET 10 is LTS and still supports the original x86-64 baseline |\n| **Cross-compile a separate build** | Publish with `dotnet publish -r linux-x64` using a .NET 10 SDK targeting that node specifically |\n\nThere is no runtime flag to bypass the baseline check — it's a hard requirement baked into the JIT and runtime libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5cdc3f6c-70ff-49dc-89e2-059669683114","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. But actually, let me think more carefully.\n\n.NET 9 did NOT change the baseline. Let me reconsider.\n\n\nActually, I need to clarify the x86-64 microarchitecture levels: the original baseline supports SSE and SSE2, while v2 adds SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B from around 2009-2011, and v3 adds AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, FMA, LZCNT, and MOVBE from 2013-2015.\n\nFor .NET specifically, there's been discussion about raising the baseline from x86-64-v1 to v2 in a future release. Given that .NET 10 launches in November 2025 and .NET 11 would follow in November 2026, the user's May 2026 timeframe falls right in that window. The proposal would mean older .NET versions targeted just the original x86-64-v1 instruction set, while newer versions would require v2 or potentially even v3 support—which could be problematic for hardware from around 2012 that might not have all those instructions. Looking at the GitHub issue about raising the baseline to x86-64-v2, that seems like the more conservative approach. For .NET 11 in 2026, they'd likely go with v2 since it covers most hardware from 2008 onward, though v3 with AVX2 is also possible if they're being more aggressive—that would cut off anything before Haswell in 2013. The CPUs that would actually fail x86-64-v2 are pre-2009 models, so 2012 hardware shouldn't have that problem. I'm thinking the baseline was probably raised to x86-64-v3 instead, which requires AVX2—something Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge from 2012 don't support. That would explain why their older CPUs are hitting this instruction set error in .NET 11. the baseline requirement, which means their 2012-era hardware is missing some of the required instruction sets. Since only one Linux node is failing while the others work fine, it's likely that one particular CPU is just old enough to lack the necessary instructions that .NET 11 now expects.","outputTokens":2272,"requestId":"2843:2AB0E:156ECCE:1817820:6A0285AD"},"id":"d744ee01-519f-437d-8a4e-aa95ecff795e","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:43:58.832Z","parentId":"